<br>
My main is a 65 Pally on Torv. I had been looking for Brell's Stalwart Shield for many levels in preparation for the day I dinged 65 and only saw it once for 50k (it's amazing how many people expect you to have it the second you're 65!). Last night I finally saw it again for 35k. So, I borrowed 20k from a friend because I only had 15k (can't believe I just used the phrase &quot;ONLY had 15k&quot;!) and now I am 20k in debt (which is more plat than I've ever seen). I have a chanter alt level 52 who I love to play as well. Will I make the money it takes to pay off my friend and then buy KEI when she's 60? Answer: No way! So, I will likely go into debt again. Will I ask for donations for KEI to help repay that friend? Answer: absoltely! I won't set a particular price and of course donations from friends, group-mates and guildies will be refused, but from others I will ask for donations (though I'm not certain I can take the boredom involved with sitting around PoK for hours on end).<br>
<br>
Like someone a few pages ago stated (sorry I don't remember who said it), someone, somewhere got that spell as a drop and is gouging some enchanter by pricing it high in the bazaar. That same person could be the one expecting free KEI at a moments notice from 5 zones away, who knows. But in any case, they weren't trying to help their fellow player when putting it up for sale for so much, they were trying to make cash... and actually, I can't blame them for that. I'm sure they need the money for something as dear to them as KEI or any other spell is to us. But then we need to make back the money somehow! I haven't even looked into the post 60 level spells, they may be just as unaffordable and my goal will just be to be out of debt by then!<br>
<br>
It all goes round and round really... This enchanter borrows money to buy KEI from the warrior (so I can do my expected job). The warrior uses the money to buy uber weapons with great procs to keep agro (so he can do his expected job). The cleric that sold the uber weapon uses the money to buy dots and spells and donate for KEI for less downtime (so he can do his expected job). Then this enchanter uses the KEI donations to pay off the people who helped her buy KEI in the first place and to buy the next spell (so I can do my expected job)... ETC. If any one class stops making money, we're all in trouble. Try grouping with a caster who doesn't have their spells... try grouping with a tank that can't keep agro... try grouping with a ranger that can't shake agro... try grouping with a cleric with no mana pool... try grouping with a mage who can't summon the stuff you need to be efficient. The thing that makes all the proper gear, spells, and buffs possible is money.<br>
<br>
Factor in the fact that all melee are somewhat ninja looters in the eyes of the casters. They are there where the mob drops and the casters are all in the background sitting on their butts so they must not actually want the loot, right?! So, buffs are the casters way to make up for that. &quot;Want HoV? Then gimme back some of that loot you snagged during your last group outing where ffa was the rule&quot;. It's simple balancing really.<br>
<br>
As for clerics... I do feel their pain in the pocket book. They pay for KEI and then for dots in order to do their job as expected (people are sometimes actually angered when a cleric needs a med break these days!... Me, I see it as a chance to run to the bathroom or grab another soda or even both if I'm feeling particularly motivated for blood circulation). I carry dots as a rule and give some to the cleric as thanx for the spell. But most don't, so I completely understand when they sell HoV for cash to pay for the dots they use when grouping.<br>
<br>
Finally (I'm sure you're all sighing in relief that this is about to end <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) the chanter who wouldn't buff the raid is a gimp. That behavior is not condoned by the general populace and is the exception, not the rule. Personally I would never have anything to do with that person again if they did that to me. So, using that one situation to stereotype all chanters as greedy really isn't fair... we're just trying to survive money-wise to get the spells that everyone expects us to have, just like everyone else.<br>
<br>
<br>
Zevia Zontarr<br>
